text: We’re looking at a powerful entity that builds fine-grained psychological profiles of over two billion humans, that runs large-scale behavior manipulation experiments, and that aims at developing the best AI technology the world has ever seen. Personally, it really scares me

name: fchollet
text: Who knows what will be next. It is quite striking that Facebook has been investing enormous amounts in AI research and development, with the explicit goal of becoming a leader in the field. What does that tell you? What do you use AI/RL for when your product is a newsfeed?

name: fchollet
text: AI has been making fast progress in recent years, and that progress is only beginning to get deployed in targeting algorithms and social media bots. Deep learning has only started to make its way into newsfeeds and ad networks around 2016. Facebook has invested massively in it

name: fchollet
text: It is the reason why so many of the ads you see online seem desperately irrelevant. They aren't that sophisticated. Likewise, the social media bots used by hostile state actors to sway public opinion have little to no AI in them. They’re all extremely primitive. For now.

name: fchollet
text: Until 2015, all ad targeting algorithms across the industry were running on mere logistic regression. In fact, that’s still true to a large extent today -- only the biggest players have switched to more advanced models.

name: fchollet
text: So, if mass population control is already possible today -- in theory -- why hasn’t the world ended yet? In short, I think it’s because we’re really bad at AI. But that may be about to change. You see, our technical capabilities are the bottleneck here.

name: fchollet
text: Importantly, mass population control -- in particular political control -- arising from placing AI algorithms in charge of our information diet does not necessarily require very advanced AI. You don’t need self-aware, superintelligent AI for this to be a dire threat.

name: fchollet
text: The human mind is a static, vulnerable system that will come increasingly under attack from ever-smarter AI algorithms that will simultaneously have a complete view of everything we do and believe, and complete control of the information we consume.

name: fchollet
text: In the case of the human mind, these vulnerabilities never get patched, they are just the way we work. They’re in our DNA. They're our psychology. On a personal level, we have no practical way to defend ourselves against them.

name: fchollet
text: Some of them have been used for a long time in advertising (e.g. positive/negative social reinforcement), but in a very weak, un-targeted form. From an information security perspective, you would call these "vulnerabilities": known exploits that can be used to take over a system.

name: fchollet
text: This is made all the easier by the fact that the human mind is highly vulnerable to simple patterns of social manipulation. While thinking about these issues, I have compiled a short list of psychological attack patterns that would be devastatingly effective

name: fchollet
text: A good chunk of the field of AI research (especially the bits that Facebook has been investing in) is about developing algorithms to solve such optimization problems as efficiently as possible, to close the loop and achieve full control of the phenomenon at hand. In this case, us

name: fchollet
text: A loop in which you observe the current state of your targets and keep tuning what information you feed them, until you start observing the opinions and behaviors you wanted to see

name: fchollet
text: In short, Facebook can simultaneously measure everything about us, and control the information we consume. When you have access to both perception and action, you’re looking at an AI problem. You can start establishing an optimization loop for human behavior. A RL loop.

name: fchollet
text: This is not quite news, as Facebook has been known to run since at least 2013 a series of experiments in which they were able to successfully control the moods and decisions of unwitting users by tuning their newsfeeds’ contents, as well as prediction user's future decisions

name: fchollet
text: If Facebook gets to decide, over the span of many years, which news you will see (real or fake), whose political status updates you’ll see, and who will see yours, then Facebook is in effect in control of your political beliefs and your worldview

name: fchollet
text: Integrated over many years of exposure, the algorithmic curation of the information we consume gives the systems in charge considerable power over our lives, over who we become. By moving our lives to the digital realm, we become vulnerable to that which rules it -- AI algorithms

name: fchollet
text: These two trends overlap at the level of the algorithms that shape our digital content consumption. Opaque social media algorithms get to decide, to an ever-increasing extent, which articles we read, who we keep in touch with, whose opinions we read, whose feedback we get

name: fchollet
text: The world is being shaped in large part by two long-time trends: first, our lives are increasingly dematerialized, consisting of consuming and generating information online, both at work and at home. Second, AI is getting ever smarter.

name: fchollet
text: The problem with Facebook is not *just* the loss of your privacy and the fact that it can be used as a totalitarian panopticon. The more worrying issue, in my opinion, is its use of digital information consumption as a psychological control vector. Time for a thread

name: fchollet
text: As a member of the AI research community: next you participate in Facebook's AI ecosystem in any way, think about what you are enabling. You are feeding a monster that may end up eating us all. Sorry if I sound dramatic, but the threat level we face deserves that vocabulary.

name: fchollet
text: If there's one AI risk you should be worried about, this is it: extremely effective, scalable population control. And the fact that Facebook has been attempting to become a leader in AI is genuinely terrifying when you can see the full extent of the implications

name: fchollet
text: Facebook has been running for a long time a very "successful" series of experiments about using the newsfeed to control users' moods and opinions, as well as predicting users' future decisions (e.g. predicting breakups and new relationships)

text:
Essentially:
- As a TF user, leverage the high-level functionality of tf.keras to define your TF models
- If you're using Keras on top of TF and you seek better integration with TF features, switch to tf.keras

name: fchollet
text: Let's be clear: there isn't any "TF *or* Keras" choice to make. Keras is an API, rather than a standalone framework, and it's the official high-level API of TF (via tf.keras). You should use TF *and* Keras! A powerful combination, both easy-to-use and flexible/extensible.

text: Seemed to me that for successful giant tech companies, the fundamental tech breakthroughs take place before the startup gets formed, then the seed funding is used to find product/market fit, then the big $ is used to scale. Is this naive? Are there historical counter-examples?

name: fchollet
text: @hardmaru It's a good thing that the next generation is moving up the abstraction stack, telling students to go back to the start is not a good learning strategy in my opinion

name: fchollet
text: @hardmaru Plenty of ppl are proficient with NNs without ever having implemented their own -- they know how it works, but never dealt with the impl details. 10 years from now this will be 90% of us. Same as how current SWEs know how an OS works but have never built their own toy OS

name: fchollet
text: @hardmaru I wrote my first neural nets (actually in C) as a student in 2009. Taught me more about C than about NNs. It took me a few more years until I started understanding what neural nets do and what makes them useful. The key was better tools + application to many real-world datasets

name: fchollet
text: @hardmaru Grad students knew how to implement neural nets in C in 2000. And they didn't have good intuition about them. A high school student playing with NN frameworks in 2018 can develop stronger understanding of NNs in a matter of days -- just thanks to a better application context

name: fchollet
text:
@hardmaru It's perhaps clearer with a simpler example: implementing SVD teaches you how to implement SVD. Once you're done, you still don't know what it does.

Using SVD on various datasets and plotting  using the results is what gives you intuition about SVD. Also, learning math

name: fchollet
text:
@hardmaru Knowing the algorithm != Knowing how/why it works.

My recommendation: do Kaggle competitions, and use more than neural nets. Use many different ML models. Make it visual. Plot your features.

name: fchollet
text:
@hardmaru Implementing neural nets teaches you how to implement neural nets. It gives you an algorithmic understanding of how they work.

It doesn't teach you what they do, or what they can or can't achieve. To learn that, you should apply them on a range of real problems (not XOR/MNIST)

text: @opencpu @itschekkers @hadleywickham @jalapic @JennyBryan @rogierK @SachaEpskamp @amuellerml @soumithchintala Since I see that the OP has a startup, I would say one option is to do dual-license AGPL but require a CLA from contributors (so _you_ can still use the software for commercial / closed source use, but they cannot)

name: wesmckinn
text: @wligtenberg @hadleywickham @opencpu @itschekkers @jalapic @JennyBryan @rogierK @SachaEpskamp @amuellerml @soumithchintala well, they _are_ developers, but their product is often science! =)

text: Nothing quite like a cordial discussion about opinions on OSS licenses to get people sending nasty comments to me on private channels. Happy new year everyone

name: wesmckinn
text: @hadleywickham @opencpu @itschekkers @jalapic @JennyBryan @rogierK @SachaEpskamp @amuellerml @soumithchintala It's true. I would say R is a special case among programming lang's because a higher % of R users (compared with, say, Python or C++) are end-users rather than software engineers building libraries or systems for commercial use

name: wesmckinn
text: @opencpu @itschekkers @hadleywickham @jalapic @JennyBryan @rogierK @SachaEpskamp @amuellerml @soumithchintala the exception is building end-user applications (like IDEs, text editors, etc.) which won't be used as dependencies in other projects (e.g. Emacs). Then GPL won't hurt you

name: wesmckinn
text: @opencpu @itschekkers @hadleywickham @jalapic @JennyBryan @rogierK @SachaEpskamp @amuellerml @soumithchintala yes, my recommendation is to use permissive (Apache/MIT/BSD) _unless_ you are dual-license (GPL/commercial) or closed source. Being GPL-only will generally just drive away contributors and users

text: @jreback 8/ We will figure it out though, we have to. </thread>

name: wesmckinn
text: @jreback 7/ The fact that we've gotten as far as we have on so little resources is amazing, and a testiment to the devs' resilience.

name: wesmckinn
text: @jreback 6/ We want to keep making open source data science work for the rest of our lives. It is important that we figure out a way to do that.

text: @teoliphant It may be a Bazaar, but luckily it's a bazaar full of experienced data system developers who care about open source

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant As the mantra goes: "Community over Code". Even though we're focusing on different parts of the problem, it's the same problem space

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant I don't see a reason for things to be so separate. I would like to see a list of things we do to help you succeed, and vice versa

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant @choldgraf @ChrisFiloG I'm skeptical about whether this is practical / possible. It would be a good exercise ("test case") for ndtypes to be made to describe Arrow

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant as soon as you commit to a precise memory representation (that you memory map), it's very hard to change that

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant personally, i don't care about the compute engine and the type metadata, because any given system will implement their own versions.

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant right, but the calc engine needs a memory format, unless it's based on a format-agnostic iterator (but that doesn't seem very efficient)

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant without a well-specified memory representation, I'm not sure what you have. The community will be interested to understand better, and help

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant Start a mailing list. A lot of people don't have time/resources to be where the discussion is happening.

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant As you say "I know what to do here, I just need the funds and the people to do it." You need to achieve consensus

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant Those are different projects. Something so important as generalizing the buffer protocol needs to be a community-led initiative

name: wesmckinn
text: On OSS culture: "Making important decisions in private is like spraying contributor repellant on your project."

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant @ApacheArrow As a result, we have over 40 contributors, with various stages of language interfaces in C, C++, Python, Ruby, Java, Scala, Javascript

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant In @ApacheArrow we have been running a 100% open and transparent process: open design, open discussions, open development.

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant As far as I can tell, your design process is happening behind closed doors. That doesn't produce healthy OSS communities.

name: wesmckinn
text: @teoliphant Do you have specification documents for the memory format you are proposing? Type metadata is a comparatively simple problem
